</figure>
<para id="para-00004">The steps in the solid-phase procedure have been improved substantially over the years, but the fundamental idea remains the same. A common procedure is use of the Wang resin, developed by Su-Sun Wang, with the Fmoc protecting group. Less common is using the PAM (phenylacetamidomethyl) resin with Boc as the N-protecting group.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
<media alt="An illustration shows the structures of Wang resin PAM resin and Fmoc-protected amino acid. Wang resin shows a 4-carbon chain wherein C2 shows a methylene group with an open bond on the left intersected by a pink spiral line C2 shows methine group; C3 shows methylene group and C4 shows a methine group having an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line. C2 and C4 are bonded to benzene rings at the bottom; the benzene attached to C2 is further bonded to a carbon bonded to oxygen bonded to a benzene bonded to a carbon bonded to a pink oxygen bonded to a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) whose carbon is bonded to another carbon bonded to R1 wedge bonded to hydrogen and dash bonded to blue NHFmoc. PAM resin shows a 4-carbon chain wherein C2 shows a methylene group with an open bond on the left intersected by a pink spiral line C2 shows methine group; C3 shows methylene group and C4 shows a methine group having an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line. C2 and C4 are bonded to benzene rings at the bottom; the benzene attached to C2 is further bonded to a carbon bonded to NH bonded to a carbonyl group whose carbon is bonded to a carbon bonded to benzene bonded to a carbon bonded to pink oxygen bonded to a carbonyl group whose carbon is bonded to another carbon bonded to R1 wedge bonded to hydrogen and dash bonded to blue NHFmoc. The structure of Fmoc-protected amino acid shows benzene fused to a cyclopentane fused to another benzene; the tip of cyclopentane is bonded to a hydrogen and to a carbon bonded to an oxygen bonded to a carbonyl group whose carbon is bonded to blue NH bonded to a methine bonded to R at the bottom the methine is further bonded to a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) whose carbon is bonded to a pink oxygen that has an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_26_08_003.jpg"/></media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00005">Robotic peptide synthesizers are now used to automatically repeat the coupling, washing, and deprotection steps with different amino acids. Each step occurs in high yield, and mechanical losses are minimized because the peptide intermediates are never removed from the insoluble polymer until the final step. Peptides with 20 amino acids can be routinely prepared in a few hours.</para>
